<dl id="n06032k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06032k">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06032k"> 32(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the vista of time ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n06032k"> <li>FW prototext </li><li><ms href="#n06032k">MS BL 47471b-87v</ms> </li><li>JJA 48:032 <a name="h11d" href="../../FF/fdra/hda.htm#h11d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/h/h11d.htm#n06032k">Draft: I.8&sect;1.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;Sir Samuel Ferguson&rsquo; Moreover, another Belfast friend and mentor, Dr. Robert Gordon, was keeping him up to his highest poetical self by a series of memorable letters, extracts from which Lady Ferguson gives in her Biography of Sir Samuel, as thus: &ldquo;You rejoice me, I speak seriously, by saying you are &lsquo;doing&rsquo;. To be and to do. O Ferguson, these little words contain the sum of all man&apos;s destiny. You are strong, and I would have you strike some stroke that will reverberate down <mark>the vista of time</mark>. Will you, Ferguson?&rdquo; <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS2"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) 41</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
